âœ… The Key Idea
ğŸ§  Lambdas can be used anywhere a functional interface is expected.

â“What is a Functional Interface?
================================
A functional interface is an interface with only one abstract method.
ğŸ”¸ Runnable is a classic example:

@FunctionalInterface
public interface Runnable {
    void run(); // only one abstract method
}

âœ… Since Runnable has exactly one method, Java allows us to use a lambda in place of creating a Runnable object.


âœ… How This Works with submit()
================================
The submit() method in ExecutorService has this signature:
Future<?> submit(Runnable task)

Now, when you do this:
executor.submit(() -> {
    System.out.println("Hello from thread!");
});
You are:
Passing a lambda that matches Runnable's method signature: void run()
So Java automatically converts this lambda into a Runnable object.

Itâ€™s as if you had written:
Runnable task = new Runnable() {
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Hello from thread!");
    }
};
executor.submit(task);



ğŸ” How to Identify When You Can Use a Lambda
============================================
Any time a method expects a functional interface, you can pass a lambda.

âœ… Common functional interfaces in Java:
| Interface       | Method Signature   | Can use Lambda? |
| --------------- | ------------------ | --------------- |
| `Runnable`      | `void run()`       | âœ… Yes           |
| `Callable<T>`   | `T call()`         | âœ… Yes           |
| `Consumer<T>`   | `void accept(T t)` | âœ… Yes           |
| `Function<T,R>` | `R apply(T t)`     | âœ… Yes           |
| `Supplier<T>`   | `T get()`          | âœ… Yes           |

So if a method accepts any of these, or your own interface with one method, you can use a lambda.



â— If the interface had multiple abstract methods?
Then lambdas would NOT work.
Lambdas only replace functional interfaces.


âœ… Summary
==========
| Concept                          | Explanation                                 |
| -------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------- |
| Functional Interface             | Interface with 1 abstract method            |
| Runnable is Functional Interface | âœ… Yes (`void run()`)                        |
| Lambda `() -> {}`                | Matches `Runnable` â€” no args, no return     |
| Java behavior                    | Automatically converts lambda to `Runnable` |


